Mount Dukono, located on Halmahera Island in Indonesiaâ€™s Maluku Province, is one of the most active volcanoes in the region. As a stratovolcano, it has frequent eruptions, emitting powerful ash plumes and lava flows that captivate both researchers and adventurers. The volcanoâ€™s geological features make it a prime subject for volcanology studies. Its eruptions are often unpredictable, making it an exciting yet dangerous destination for those seeking a volcano adventure. Situated in a remote destination, Dukono is a spectacular sight, representing the raw power of nature. It remains one of the most notable active volcanoes in Indonesia.

Getting to Stoos
1. Drive to the Schwyz-Schlattli funicular station:
â€¢ Address: Schlattli, 6433 Schwyz, Switzerland.
â€¢ Parking is available near the base station of the Stoos funicular.
â€¢ Ensure you arrive early, especially during weekends or peak seasons, as parking spots can fill up quickly.
2. Take the Stoosbahn Funicular:
â€¢ The Stoosbahn is the steepest funicular in the world and takes you from Schlattli up to the car-free village of Stoos in just a few minutes.
â€¢ Tickets: Purchase tickets for the funicular at the station or online to save time.

The Hike

Starting Point: Klingenstock
â€¢ From Stoos village, take the chairlift to Klingenstock.
â€¢ The chairlift ride offers stunning views and saves time and energy before starting the ridge hike.

The Ridge Hike: Klingenstock to Fronalpstock
â€¢ Duration: 3-4 hours (7 km).
â€¢ Highlights:
â€¢ Stunning panoramic views of the surrounding mountains (e.g., Mythen, Rigi, Pilatus).
â€¢ Views of Lake Lucerne and the countless peaks of central Switzerland.
â€¢ Well-marked paths and a mix of steep sections, ridges, and scenic spots.

End Point: Fronalpstock
â€¢ At Fronalpstock, take in the breathtaking 360-degree views.
â€¢ From here, take the chairlift back down to Stoos village.
